\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A previous study which considered equal dispersal rates across the sexes
 showed that limited dispersal favors a lower female age at maturity, yet
 a higher male age at maturity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Johnstone2014"

\end_inset

, at least when there is a slight degree of nonlocal mating 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell<1$
\end_inset

.
 The same pattern is found in the current study for males, yet not for females:
 to recapatulate the result for males from the previous study, in viscous
 populations with a slight degree of nonlocal mating, an increase in male
 fecundity results in more sirings in remote patches, whereas an increase
 in male juvenile survival leads to more competition among males in the
 local patch, favoring a higher male age at maturity.
 The same pattern, although for slightly different reasons, is found here:
 an increase in male age at maturity leads to a higher fertily (both in
 remote 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, things are different when the sexes differ in dispersal, as limited
 dispersal by one sex always selects for an increase in the age at maturity
 of that sex.
 Why is this the case? When females are the more philopatric sex, an increase
 in a female's age at maturity (and hence an increase in fecundity) now
 leads to less kin competition overall: although more daughters are produced
 who will compete with each other, also more sons are produced, who disperse
 and compete for breeding positions elsewhere.
 By contrast, an increase in a female's juvenile survival increases competition
 among philopatric female relatives, yet has no effect on dispersing males.
 Hence, in the presence of sex-differences in dispersal, we would predict
 that the more philopatric sex has the highest age at maturity.
 
\end_layout

